  ## 📌 Personal AI Agents like Moltbot Are a Security Nightmare
  
  [Amy Chang](https://www.linkedin.com/article/edit/7421868819025059841/#) and [Vineeth Sai Narajala](https://www.linkedin.com/article/edit/7421868819025059841/#) explain why Moltbot’s “skills” model is dangerous: it can execute local commands, touch files, and leak credentials, and malicious skills can hide prompt-injection and data-exfiltration steps — so [Cisco](https://www.linkedin.com/article/edit/7421868819025059841/#) released the open-source Skill Scanner to flag risky skill content before it’s installed. [https://blogs.cisco.com/ai/personal-ai-agents-like-moltbot-are-a-security-nightmare](https://blogs.cisco.com/ai/personal-ai-agents-like-moltbot-are-a-security-nightmare)
  
  ![](https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:684/0*JqSsT0pd7fq0AZQP)
  
  ## 📌 OWASP Agentic AI Top 10: Threats in the Wild
  
  [Raúl\_ Redondo](https://www.linkedin.com/article/edit/7421868819025059841/#) maps real-world agent failures to the OWASP Agentic AI Top 10, showing how prompt injection, tool misuse, insecure data flows, and weak isolation show up in practical deployments, not just theory. [https://labs.lares.com/owasp-agentic-top-10](https://labs.lares.com/owasp-agentic-top-10/)
  
